# Parallel Data Import in DuckDB Extensions

The issue is that **`DataChunk::SetValue` is not thread-safe** — it mutates shared data structures (especially the validity mask) without synchronization. You cannot call it from multiple threads on the same `DataChunk`.

## Recommended Solutions

### **Solution 1: Parallel Chunk Generation (Best)**

Have each worker thread build its own `DataChunk` independently, then coordinate through a thread-safe queue:

```cpp
struct ParallelReadState {
    std::queue<DataChunk> chunk_queue;
    std::mutex queue_lock;
    bool finished = false;
};

void ParallelTableFunction(ClientContext &context, TableFunctionInput &input, DataChunk &output) {
    auto &state = input.global_state->Cast<ParallelReadState>();

    // Spawn worker threads (once)
    if (!state.workers_started) {
        for (int i = 0; i < num_threads; i++) {
            std::thread([&state]() {
                DataChunk local_chunk(state.schema);
                // Read and fill local_chunk here
                // DataChunk::SetValue is safe within one thread
                for (int row = 0; row < rows; row++) {
                    local_chunk.SetValue(col, row, value);
                }
                std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(state.queue_lock);
                state.chunk_queue.push(local_chunk);
            }).detach();
        }
        state.workers_started = true;
    }

    // Main thread retrieves completed chunks
    {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(state.queue_lock);
        if (!state.chunk_queue.empty()) {
            output = state.chunk_queue.front();
            state.chunk_queue.pop();
            return;
        }
    }
}
```

### **Solution 2: Direct Vector Manipulation (Faster)**

Skip `SetValue` entirely and work directly with vector data:

```cpp
auto &col_vec = output.data[col_idx];
auto col_data = FlatVector::GetData<int32_t>(col_vec);
auto &col_validity = FlatVector::GetValidityMask(col_vec);

// Now you can fill in parallel (different rows/columns don't conflict)
col_data[row_idx] = value;
col_validity.Set(row_idx, is_valid);
```

### **Solution 3: Thread-Local Buffers + Sync**

```cpp
thread_local vector<Value> local_buffer;

// Fill from threads, then copy to output in serial
std::memcpy(output.data[col_idx], local_buffer.data(), ...);
```

## Key Takeaway

**Per-thread `DataChunk` construction is safe.** Only coordinate the final handoff back to DuckDB's main thread through a thread-safe queue or similar mechanism.

For the fastest import, **avoid `SetValue` entirely** and manipulate `Vector` data directly.

