# Appending Non-UTF8 Text to DuckDB

The issue is that DuckDB requires all string input to be **UTF-8 encoded** [5]. Your string is likely in a Windows code page (e.g., Windows-1252 or similar from the MFC system), not UTF-8.

## Solution: Convert to UTF-8 Before Appending

You need to convert your string to UTF-8 before passing it to the appender. Here's a practical approach using Windows APIs:

```cpp
#include <windows.h>
#include <string>

std::string ConvertToUTF8(const std::string& input) {
    if (input.empty()) return input;

    // First, convert from system code page to wide char (UTF-16)
    int wideSize = MultiByteToWideChar(CP_ACP, 0, input.c_str(), -1, NULL, 0);
    std::wstring wide(wideSize - 1, 0);
    MultiByteToWideChar(CP_ACP, 0, input.c_str(), -1, &wide[0], wideSize);

    // Then, convert from wide char to UTF-8
    int utf8Size = WideCharToMultiByte(CP_UTF8, 0, wide.c_str(), -1, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL);
    std::string utf8(utf8Size - 1, 0);
    WideCharToMultiByte(CP_UTF8, 0, wide.c_str(), -1, &utf8[0], utf8Size, NULL, NULL);

    return utf8;
}
```

Then use it before appending:

```cpp
std::string mfcString = "Ö"; // From your MFC system
std::string utf8String = ConvertToUTF8(mfcString);
appender->Append(utf8String.c_str());
```

## Why This Works

According to the documentation, DuckDB stores all strings as VARCHAR using UTF-8 encoding internally [5]. Your appender expects UTF-8 input, so any non-UTF8 encoded text will trigger the "Invalid unicode detected" error during flush.

**Note:** The conversion code above is not grounded in the provided DuckDB documentation but is a standard solution for Windows character encoding issues. Adjust `CP_ACP` if your MFC strings use a different code page.
